    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1907-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1907-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 803/11–12.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Imperial Chinese Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1907-02-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 25, 1907</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Referring to my note of the
                    21st of January last, giving a list of Chinese officials specially authorized by
                    my Government to issue the so-called “section 6 certificates” to Chinese of the
                    exempt class coming to the United States from other countries than China, I take
                    the liberty of suggesting that the diplomatic and consular representatives of
                    the United States abroad be instrusted to recognize and vise the certificates
                    properly issued by the Chinece officials referred to, if they are not already so
                    instructed. This will prevent a great deal of misunderstanding that may arise
                    from the issuance of those certificates.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Chentung Liang Cheng.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
